## Non-Negotiable Rules

These are enforced by plugins where possible — the bullets below are advisory reminders, not primary enforcement.

- **No AI attribution anywhere** — never mention AI, Claude, OpenAI, agent names, or TDD phases in commits, PR descriptions, code comments, documentation, or any project artifact. No `Co-Authored-By` trailers, no `Generated with` footers. Enforced by the `no-ai-attribution.ts` plugin.
- **No hardcoded secrets** — environment variables only; fail-fast at startup if a required variable is absent; never log secrets. Enforced by the `security-guard.ts` plugin.
- **No `print()` in library code** (Python) / **no `console.log` in `src/`** (TypeScript) — structured logging only.
- **No bare `except:`** (Python) — catch specific exceptions.
- **No deprecated `typing.Dict` / `typing.List`** (Python 3.10+) — use `dict`, `list`, `X | None`.
- **No `any` without justification** (TypeScript) — strict mode enforced by `tsc`.
- **Parameterised SQL only** — no string interpolation, no f-strings, no template literals with user input.
- **Coverage floors** — ≥95% for Python, ≥80% for TypeScript, on all changed files.
- **ESLint flat config must exist** in every TypeScript repo. Skipping ESLint because it is "not configured" is a defect.

---

## Commit Standard (Conventional Commits)

Format: `{type}({scope}): {description}` — types: `feat` `fix` `refactor` `test` `docs` `chore`.
Breaking change: add `!` before `:`.

- **Never** mention TDD phases, agent names, or AI in commit messages.
- **Never** add AI attribution.
- **Never** reference planning artefacts or internal labels in PR descriptions.

---

## Branch Rules

**NEVER commit directly to `main` / `master`. Always use a feature branch.**

- One branch per logical unit of work.
- Branch must be pushed to `origin` and a PR opened before merging.
- PR must pass all CI status checks before merge.
- Delete the branch locally and remotely after merge.

<!-- CUSTOMISE: optional — if you use a ticketing system, add a branch-naming rule here. -->
<!-- Example: `{type}/<PROJ>-{N}/{short-description}` — one ticket per branch. -->

---

## Observability Standards

Every new action, probe, or service endpoint must:

- Emit an OTel span with appropriate attributes (no PII, no secrets).
- Use structured logging only — no `print()`, no credentials in output.
- Follow a consistent metric naming convention (`<service>_<component>_<metric>_<unit>`).

---

## Agents Reference

Invoke with `@agent-name`. Agents live in `~/.config/opencode/agent/`. All agents are leaf agents — they do not spawn subagents.

| Agent | Role |
|-------|------|
| `@architect` | Design review, interface specs, ADRs |
| `@coder-python` | Python feature implementation (TDD) |
| `@coder-typescript` | TypeScript feature implementation (TDD) |
| `@coder-sql` | SQL / database implementation |
| `@coder-tdd` | TDD cycle facilitation (Red phase) |
| `@refactor` | Safe incremental refactoring |
| `@tester` | Test strategy, red phase, coverage analysis |
| `@reviewer` | Adversarial multi-lens code review |
| `@sre` | Deployment safety, OTel, runbooks |
| `@security` | Security review, OWASP, secrets audit |
| `@observability` | OTel instrumentation |
| `@api` | API design, OpenAPI 3.1 |
| `@data-analyst` | Data analysis, stats, visualisation |
| `@data-engineer` | Pipelines, dbt, Airflow, Spark |
| `@product-owner` | Stories, INVEST, RICE, OKRs |
| `@ai-developer` | LLM, RAG, MCP servers, evals |

---

## Commands Reference

Invoke with `/command-name`. Commands live in `~/.config/opencode/command/`.

| Command | Purpose |
|---------|---------|
| `/commit` | Conventional commit creator |
| `/pr` | Open a pull request |
| `/review` | Adversarial review of the current branch |
| `/spec` | Generate an OpenAPI 3.1 spec for a new endpoint |
| `/story` | Draft a user story |
| `/index` | Update project docs index |
| `/opsx:propose` `/opsx:apply` `/opsx:explore` `/opsx:archive` | OpenSpec workflow |

---

## Session Memory

If you use a cross-session memory layer, save session state on a regular cadence — typically every ~15 minutes and after every commit. At minimum record: active branch, what was done, what is pending, key decisions.

OpenCode does not ship a skill layer, so the guidance above comes inline via this file rather than through `/skill-name` lookups.

